Ubisoft's method of growing the esports scene is slow and steady. 

This is how you build stronger esports ecosystem that lasts long. These guys ain't dumb.

I might be wrong but currently that's my POV.

From business standpoint, I can see tons of challenges that TEC and Ubisoft are facing.

In the end,

I'm equally happy and a little bit concerned.

Now to get newer players and teams, you need to make the game fun and have less steeper learning curve. Ubisoft said that they will be rolling these things in phases. Good!

But there's a pricing concern in Developing nations like India, Pakistan, Bangladesh and Sri Lanka too.

I feel Ubisoft counted this thing as a casualty but, It's probably going to be harder for existing orgs or athletes to keep following up with the game (unless some org has deeper pockets or an athlete has alot of free time and no commitments).

Now let's see what was Ubisoft's main focus here: Promoting newer athletes and teams. 

It shouldn't be like only 3 teams dominating the entire region.
